A - Classification with Scikit-learn ML tools¶

Use case A.1 : guess the day of the week of a daily temperature sensor data time series¶

Detailed explanation : starting from a long sequence of an ambiant tempature sensor data of an office (ex : 2 months, 1 data each 15 mn), we first extract daily sequences and then a set of statistic features for each day (X input), which are each associated to the day of the week (y ouput). Classification models (different are tested and compared) are trained to match the week of the day (Sunday, Monday ....) to the daily data (either the temperature curve or the stats features) and then we try to guess the day of the week for new samples and evaluate the performance of different classification model in this case. By comparing prediction with real data day by day, we can try to understand which days are more easy to "recognise" (ex : no heating on Sunday) and try to improve the "feature" more adequat to characterise a day of temperature measurement¶

Suggestion for improvement : correlate the single temperature data with features from other device (ex : heating)

Step 8 : Pipeline : we factorize all the sequence and test in a single "pipeline" that is able to chain the transformation of initial X and y. here we pipeline a scaling, a feature selection and a KNN classification (the feature extraction has been made before the split)¶
In [27]:
# We redo the split, before the X being scaled (raw X after 4 features extraction)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y_name, 
                                        test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y_name)
# The steps of the pipeline : objects which will better work on standardized data
steps = [('scaler', StandardScaler()),
         ('selection', SelectKBest(k=2)),
        ('KNN', KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=1))]     # this model can be changed  
# Creation of the Pipeline object, which is a kind of "multiple ML model"
pipeline = Pipeline(steps)
# The pipeline is trained (fit) like a classical single model
pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)
# Prediction like a model
y_pred = pipeline.predict(X_test)
# Compute metrics
score = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)    # on obtient un score moyen de 0,56
print("Average score : ", score)
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

C - Future prediction with statsmodel ARIMA and SARIMAX¶

Use case C1 : try to forecast next future values of a temperature time (January/Feb 2017) series with ARIMA and SARIMAX models - Two cases of prediction on the same interval :¶

  • "One step ahead" : the model predict only the next step value from the last real one
  • "dynamique" : extrapolation on the whole interval from data before the interval (more difficult, less accurate)

Now, we have to determine the order of AR(p) and of MA(q) - Aucorelation Function (ACF) and partial ACF can help¶

In [39]:
s121.plot_acf_pacf(transform=True)

According to ACF and PACF, p could be 2 (or 4) and q=0, so ARIMA(2, 0, 0) - But it is better to check what is the optimal combination with auto_arima¶

In [40]:
auto_arima_results = pm.auto_arima(s121_train, start_p=1, start_q=0,
                     max_d=1, max_p=5, max_q=5,
                     stepwise=True, suppress_warnings=True, D=10, max_D=10,
                     error_action='ignore', seasonal=False)
print(auto_arima_results)

ARIMA(order=(4, 0, 0), suppress_warnings=True)

The result is (p, d, q) = (4, 0, 0), which more or less confirms our manual estimation with AD-Fuller and ACF-PACF. Now we come to create and fit an ARIMA (manual) model with these optimized orders¶

In [41]:
model_arima = ARIMA(s121_train, order=(4,0,0))
results_arima = model_arima.fit()

The latter ARIMA is only a correlation of s121 with itself - In the next one, we create an ARIMAX instance model which integrates s122 (heating) as an external data serie¶

In [42]:
model_arimax = ARIMA(s121_train, order=(4,0,0), exog=s122_train)
results_arimax = model_arimax.fit()

  • "dynamic" prediction with ARIMA
  • "dynamic" prediction with ARIMAX

s121_train.loc['2017-02-10':].plot(ax=ax, label="observed")
# Affiche des prédictions "one step ahead" pour les deux derniers jours
forecast_osa.loc['2017-02-13':].plot(ax=ax, style='r--',
                          label="One-step-ahead forecast")
# Affiche des prédictions "dynamic" ARIMA pour les deux derniers jours
forecast_dyn.loc['2017-02-13':].plot(ax=ax, style='o--', 
                                    label="Dynamic forecast")
# Affiche des prédictions "dynamic" ARIMAX  pour les deux derniers jours
forecast_dyn_exog.loc['2017-02-13':].plot(ax=ax, style='k--', 
                                     label="Dynamic forecast + s122")
# positionnement de la légende
legend = ax.legend(loc='lower left')

Provisional conclusions - We remark with no big surprise that :¶

  • one step ahead (read) correctly extrapolates next data from the 4 previous one (but this result should be studied in more details)
  • dynamic forecast gives quite a correct global trend, but does not follow the daily pattern
  • the difference with "exog" (other sensor) is not really significative, but it can't radically change the general trend

Now we can hope to improve the model mainly by taking into account the daily pattern (due to heating !), especially for the dynamic (long term) forecast¶

Firstly, we directly calculates the optimized orders for SARIMAX (too complicated and risky with manual methods) - Despite we limit the range of values for certain orders, this calculation is quite long (several minutes) and we give directly the results¶

In [46]:
auto_sarimax_results = pm.auto_arima(s121_train, 
                  # les ordres min/max ARMA en normal et seasonal
                  start_p=1, start_q=0, start_P=1, start_Q=0,
                  max_p=5, max_q=5, max_P=5, max_Q=5, 
                  seasonal=True,
                  # les ordres max de differencing pour que ce soit stationaire
                  max_d=1, max_D=2,
                  # fréquence de retour - 24 / jours
                  m=24,
                  stepwise=True, suppress_warnings=True, error_action='ignore')
print(auto_sarimax_results)

ARIMA(order=(1, 0, 0), seasonal_order=(2, 0, 1, 24), suppress_warnings=True)

The result is : ARIMA(order=(1, 0, 0), seasonal_order=(2, 0, 1, 24)) - We notice that p=1 only now (4 for the ARIMA without seasonal), probably because the daily period is more important. Then we create the corresponding SARIMAX¶

model_sarima = SARIMAX(s121_train, order=(1,0,0), seasonal_order=(2, 0, 1, 24), 
                trend='c')

print(results_sarima)

Provisional conclusions on SARIMAX and future improvements :¶

  • the main difference with SARIMA is that the dynamic forecast follow the shape of the real data (daily trend), the underestimation is probably due that the 2 days are weekly days, whereas the average is lower due to WE : we should take into account the day of the week ! (next improvement)
  • for the "one step ahead", we should calculate the difference between real data, ARIMA and SARIMAX estimation on the whole interval to better estimate it
